<paper id="1637976039"><title>Delay Analysis in Synchronous Programs</title><year>1993</year><authors><author org="Stanford, University" id="2257050880">Nicolas Halbwachs</author></authors><n_citation>133</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>199049734</reference><reference>1531802354</reference><reference>1568188239</reference><reference>1568478782</reference><reference>2043100293</reference><reference>2053294975</reference><reference>2081810835</reference><reference>2116989825</reference><reference>2132661148</reference><reference>2153439859</reference><reference>2160460506</reference><reference>2168047940</reference></references><venue id="1162450063" type="C">Computer Aided Verification</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-56922-7_28</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.50081">Program optimization</keyword><keyword weight="0.45764">Programming paradigm</keyword><keyword weight="0.45066">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.51342">Abstract interpretation</keyword><keyword weight="0.46127">Inductive programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.46191">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.45769">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.47345">Symbolic programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.502">Control flow analysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.48311">Programming language implementation</keyword><keyword weight="0.49624">Computer programming</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer Berlin Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Linear relation analysis [CH78, Hal79] has been proposed a long time ago as an abstract interpretation which permits to discover linear relations invariantly satisfied by the variables of a program. Here, we propose to apply this general method to variables used to count delays in synchronous programs. The “regular” behavior of these counters makes the results of the analysis especially precise. These results can be applied to code optimization and to the verification of real-time properties of programs.</abstract></p